## Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)

**Are AI agents just a marketing term for chatbots?**
No. While some companies misuse the term, a true AI agent is fundamentally different from a chatbot. Chatbots only converse and answer questions, whereas AI agents can autonomously plan, reason, and execute tasks using external tools and APIs.

**Can AI agents replace human employees?**
AI agents are best viewed as digital assistants rather than replacements. They excel at automating repetitive, multi-step tasks, freeing up human employees to focus on high-level strategy, creative problem-solving, and complex relationship building.

**Which is more expensive to implement?**
AI agents are generally more expensive and complex to implement than chatbots. Agents require deeper API integrations into your CRM, payment systems, and databases, as well as robust testing to ensure they act autonomously without errors. Chatbots can often be deployed quickly using existing knowledge bases.

**What is the difference between generative AI chatbots and AI agents?**
Generative AI chatbots (like ChatGPT) use LLMs to generate text-based responses to prompts. AI agents also use LLMs, but they use them as a "brain" to determine which tools to use and actions to take to achieve a specific goal, rather than just generating text.

